expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>750</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Feature</fr:taxon><fr:addr>jms-00EY</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00EY.xml</fr:route><fr:title>Experimental support for objects</fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2023</fr:year><fr:month>11</fr:month><fr:day>19</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
href="jonmsterling.xml"
type="local"
addr="jonmsterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-00CW</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>To facilitate the development of extensible macro libraries for diagramming and other tasks, <fr:link
href="jms-00CW.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00CW">Forester 3.0</fr:link> introduces experimental support for <fr:em>objects</fr:em> — which should be thought of as combination of records/structs, closures, and general recursion. An object is created like so:</fr:p><fr:pre>\def\my-object{
  \object[self]{
    [method1]{
      the implementation of this method
    }
    [method2]{
      the implementation of another method
      \self#method1
    }
  }
}</fr:pre><fr:p>The variable <fr:code>self</fr:code> is explicitly bound, and can be bound to any name you like. Methods currently are not allowed to take any arguments, but this may change in the future. A primitive form of inheritance is supported, using <fr:code>\patch</fr:code>:</fr:p><fr:pre>\patch{\my-object}[self]{
  [method1]{
    \self/super#method1
    some further code
  }
}</fr:pre><fr:p>The support for objects in <fr:link
href="jms-00CW.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00CW">Forester 3.0</fr:link> is extremely experimental and preliminary: users are discouraged from relying on it.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
